From: evdi-5120x1440-fix
Subject: [PATCH 1/2] connector: bypass pixel_area_limit rejection for resolutions within 8K bounds

The pixel_area_limit is set by the DisplayLinkManager userspace daemon
via EVDI_IOC_CONNECT ioctl. On some docks (e.g. ThinkPad Hybrid USB-C
Dock, USB ID 17e9:6015) the daemon sets this limit too conservatively,
causing 5120x1440 (32:9 at 1440p) to be rejected even though the
hardware supports the resolution on Windows with the same dock.

The pixel_per_second_limit already correctly constrains throughput.
The area check adds a redundant cap that blocks valid modes: 5120x1440
at 60 Hz produces fewer pixels/sec than 3840x1080 at 120 Hz, which the
same dock accepts.

Change the area rejection to only apply for resolutions exceeding 8K
(7680x4320), which is the hardware maximum defined in evdi_modeset.c.

Tested-on: Samsung Odyssey G93SC (32:9, 5120x1440) via ThinkPad Hybrid
           USB-C with USB-A Dock (17e9:6015), Linux 6.17, EVDI 1.14.16

Signed-off-by: evdi-5120x1440-fix
---
 evdi_connector.c | 3 ++-
 1 file changed, 2 insertions(+), 1 deletion(-)

--- a/evdi_connector.c
+++ b/evdi_connector.c
@@ -94,7 +94,8 @@ static enum drm_mode_status evdi_mode_valid(struct drm_connector *connector,
 	if (evdi->pixel_per_second_limit == 0)
 		return MODE_OK;

-	if (area_limit > evdi->pixel_area_limit) {
+	if (area_limit > evdi->pixel_area_limit &&
+	    area_limit > (uint32_t)(7680 * 4320)) {
 		EVDI_WARN(
 			"(card%d) Mode %dx%d@%d rejected. Reason: mode area too big\n",
 			evdi->dev_index,
